<subSubSection id="DAB513890E574CAB89BE5B76DB195AC9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEBFA6F81C33AAB145BF737B7EBF61B" lastPageNumber="2" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="394130DC9BF382A6F7194A9A79B708B5" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1FBBEB5D-AE2A-469D-8189-43AEF16A1C2A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Plesiopidae" genus="Acanthoplesiops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Acanthoplesiops Regan 1912:266" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Acanthoplesiops</taxonomicName>
is considered to have four valid species, all very small with no specimens larger than 27 mm SL. The genus is unique among acanthoclinines (and plesiopids) in having the following characters: 1-2 secondary opercular spines (Smith-Vaniz &amp; Johnson 1990: 249, mistakenly reported that 
<taxonomicName id="9A078BB56AA819BFF9E5A21552D5AE6A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4EC0904A-5351-4692-A035-763A44C5857C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Plesiopidae" genus="Fraudella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Fraudella Whitley 1935:229" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Fraudella</taxonomicName>
“has a series of prominent spines on the posterior margin of the opercle”; the serrations are actually on the preopercle); pectoral radial formula 3-0-1; supracleithral lateral-line canal absent; anterior/posterior ceratohyal suturing both medial and lateral; scales in mid-lateral series bilobed. Smith-Vaniz and Johnson (1990) noted a distributional puzzle presented by 
<taxonomicName id="51A98C9B9CC33FC81F0FD07EBE1ED10C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1FBBEB5D-AE2A-469D-8189-43AEF16A1C2A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Plesiopidae" genus="Acanthoplesiops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Acanthoplesiops Regan 1912:266" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Acanthoplesiops</taxonomicName>
in that there is no Australian representative. Mooi and Gill (in press) addressed this by providing evidence that 
<taxonomicName id="63C38320FF98495DD57BA0313A830FA2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E9B97F61-7EB1-48D8-A2F7-F2997C189A7D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Plesiopidae" genus="Notograptus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notograptus Günther 1867:63" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notograptus</taxonomicName>
, an Australian endemic and previously a separate family, is sister to 
<taxonomicName id="06AE9A153F06747155DB10D25DE9187E" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1FBBEB5D-AE2A-469D-8189-43AEF16A1C2A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Plesiopidae" genus="Acanthoplesiops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Acanthoplesiops Regan 1912:266" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Acanthoplesiops</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
